[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":326},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2019\u002F07\u002F01\u002Fnodejs-express-generator\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2019\u002F07\u002F01\u002Fnodejs-express-generator\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2019\u002F07\u002F01\u002Fnodejs-express-generator\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2019\u002F07\u002F01\u002Fnodejs-express-generator\u002F":302,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2019\u002F07\u002F01\u002Fnodejs-express-generator\u002F":311},"\u002Fnodejs\u002F20190701\u002F3784687574\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":283,"date":284,"description":285,"extension":286,"lang":287,"meta":288,"navigation":289,"path":290,"readingMinutes":291,"seo":292,"standalone":293,"stem":294,"tags":295,"tldr":299,"updated":299,"url":300,"__hash__":301},"content\u002Fen\u002FNodejs\u002Fnodejs-express-generator.md","Node.js Basics, Part 22: Scaffolding with Express Application Generator","7846875743",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":274},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,32,63,66,70,85,92,95,101,106,109,113,128,135,144,150,153,184,188,199,202,208,227,232,235,241,246,249,255,259,270],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"We've pretty much covered the Express basics, but by now you're probably wondering: do you really have to set everything up one piece at a time every time you write Express? Nope. Let me introduce a super handy tool — the Express application generator.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"setting-up","Setting up",[17,25,26,27,31],{},"Before using it, you need to install a package called ",[28,29,30],"code",{},"express-generator",":",[33,34,39],"pre",{"className":35,"code":36,"language":37,"meta":38,"style":38},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","npm install --g express-generator\n","js","",[28,40,41],{"__ignoreMap":38},[42,43,46,50,54,57,60],"span",{"class":44,"line":45},"line",1,[42,47,49],{"class":48},"sMAXC","npm install ",[42,51,53],{"class":52},"sWyjQ","--",[42,55,56],{"class":48},"g express",[42,58,59],{"class":52},"-",[42,61,62],{"class":48},"generator\n",[17,64,65],{},"(Note: this has to be installed globally.)",[12,67,69],{"id":68},"how-to-use-it","How to use it",[17,71,72,73,76,77,80,81,84],{},"First, open an empty ",[28,74,75],{},"project"," folder, open CMD, and ",[28,78,79],{},"cd"," into it. Then in the command line, type ",[28,82,83],{},"express --view=ejs"," — and something pretty magical happens.",[17,86,87],{},[88,89],"img",{"alt":90,"src":91},"All the Express files have been generated","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FpwK8YrV.png",[17,93,94],{},"You might ask why I didn't lead with this super handy tool. It's because if you jumped straight to express-generator, you probably wouldn't understand what's inside it.",[17,96,97,98,31],{},"So let's look at what it generated. First, ",[28,99,100],{},"app.js",[17,102,103],{},[88,104],{"alt":100,"src":105},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FtGDugOO.png",[17,107,108],{},"You'll find you already understand 60–70% of it, so I won't go over it again — the routing part is the same as what we wrote earlier.",[12,110,112],{"id":111},"express-generator-commands","express-generator commands",[17,114,115,116,119,120,123,124,127],{},"Now let's circle back to what that command actually meant. ",[28,117,118],{},"express"," creates the application, and ",[28,121,122],{},"--view=ejs"," means use the EJS template. If you want pug instead, type ",[28,125,126],{},"--view=pug",".",[17,129,130,131,134],{},"You can also develop your frontend pages with SCSS — just add ",[28,132,133],{},"--css=sass",". But there's one spot you need to change, otherwise it won't be able to read SCSS files.",[17,136,137,138,140,141,127],{},"In ",[28,139,100],{},", change the spot the arrow points to to ",[28,142,143],{},"false",[17,145,146],{},[88,147],{"alt":148,"src":149},"SCSS","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002F9GkCR9c.png",[17,151,152],{},"Full command for ejs + SCSS:",[33,154,156],{"className":35,"code":155,"language":37,"meta":38,"style":38},"express --view=ejs --css=sass\n",[28,157,158],{"__ignoreMap":38},[42,159,160,163,165,168,171,174,176,179,181],{"class":44,"line":45},[42,161,162],{"class":48},"express ",[42,164,53],{"class":52},[42,166,167],{"class":48},"view",[42,169,170],{"class":52},"=",[42,172,173],{"class":48},"ejs ",[42,175,53],{"class":52},[42,177,178],{"class":48},"css",[42,180,170],{"class":52},[42,182,183],{"class":48},"sass\n",[12,185,187],{"id":186},"starting-express","Starting Express",[17,189,190,191,194,195,198],{},"Before using it, remember to run ",[28,192,193],{},"npm install"," first. After that, run ",[28,196,197],{},"npm start"," to launch it in the browser.",[17,200,201],{},"(The default port is usually 3000.)",[17,203,204],{},[88,205],{"alt":206,"src":207},"localhost:3000","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fg3Tuljp.png",[17,209,210,211,214,215,218,219,222,223,226],{},"It'll automatically use ",[28,212,213],{},"node app.js",". If you want to switch to ",[28,216,217],{},"nodemon app.js",", just open ",[28,220,221],{},"package.json"," and change the ",[28,224,225],{},"start"," script.",[17,228,229],{},[88,230],{"alt":213,"src":231},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FavI7gqA.png",[17,233,234],{},"(Do not use nodemon when deploying — it will absolutely cause problems.)",[17,236,237,238,31],{},"If you want to change the port, open ",[28,239,240],{},"\u002Fbin\u002Fwww",[17,242,243],{},[88,244],{"alt":240,"src":245},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FZngQWZW.png",[17,247,248],{},"Then adjust the spot the red arrow points to.",[17,250,251],{},[88,252],{"alt":253,"src":254},"Changing the port","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FfxwW8He.png",[12,256,258],{"id":257},"one-more-thing","One more thing",[17,260,261,262,269],{},"Last, here's the ",[263,264,268],"a",{"href":265,"rel":266},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.npmjs.com\u002Fpackage\u002Fexpress-generator",[267],"nofollow","official docs"," for express-generator.",[271,272,273],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}",{"title":38,"searchDepth":275,"depth":275,"links":276},2,[277,278,279,280,281,282],{"id":14,"depth":275,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":275,"text":23},{"id":68,"depth":275,"text":69},{"id":111,"depth":275,"text":112},{"id":186,"depth":275,"text":187},{"id":257,"depth":275,"text":258},"Nodejs","2019-07-01 20:06:42","We've covered the Express basics, but by now you're probably wondering — do you really have to set everything up one piece at a time every time? Nope. This post covers a super handy tool: the Express application generator.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002Fnodejs-express-generator","2",{"title":6,"description":285},false,"en\u002FNodejs\u002Fnodejs-express-generator",[296,297,298],"Node.js","Full-Stack Warrior's Path Node.js","Express",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2019\u002F07\u002F01\u002Fnodejs-express-generator\u002F","MIwDp3S4ZuymG82VCv0wJFDz9vHil4X6NjkQBLCd1V8",{"newer":303,"older":307},{"url":304,"title":305,"date":306},"\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2019\u002F07\u002F02\u002Ffullstack-warrior-nodejs-01-firebase-express-todolist\u002F","Fullstack Warrior Node.js: Wiring Firebase + Express into a Tiny Todo App (1)","2019-07-02 09:20:36",{"url":308,"title":309,"date":310},"\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2019\u002F07\u002F01\u002Fnodejs-express-modular-routes\u002F","Node.js Basics, Part 21: Modularizing Express